Estimating the demand for rail freight transport in Pakistan: A time series analysis
Muhammad Zamir Khan *, Farzana Naheed Khan
School of Economics, Quaid-i-Azam University, Islamabad, Pakistan

ARTICLE INFO
Keywords: Rail freight transport demand ECM Johansen co-integration Gross value added Ton-kilometers

ABSTRACT
The empirical knowledge of the demand for rail transport is vital for making effective decisions regarding rail transport planning and management. To this objective, this paper provides an empirical analysis of rail freight transport demand in Pakistan using annual time series data from 1972 to 2017. The Johansen’s co-integration and error-correction model is used to estimate short and long-run elasticities. The results show that both aggregate economic activity (gross value added) and freight rate are the most significant determinants of rail freight demand in Pakistan. In particular, the long-run elasticities of rail freight demand with respect to freight rate and economic activity are À 0.39 and 0.84 while in the short-run, these elasticities are À 0.28 and 0.51, respectively. Moreover, the long-run cross price elasticity of rail freight demand is significant and positive, which implies that road and rail transport are substitutes for freight. The speed of adjustment coefficient, based on error correction model, indicates that rail freight transport ad­ justs at a moderate rate to restore long-run equilibrium relationship, with about 53% of the adjustment takes place in the first year.

1. Introduction
At macro level, freight mobility plays an important role in a country’s competitiveness, economic growth and regional connectivity. A well-established transport system facilitates the smooth freight movements in a cost-efficient manner from origins to destinations. There exist a number of modes such as road, rail, air and pipelines to handle such freight movements. However, road and rail are the two basic modes of carrying most of the country’s inland freight transport (see, for example, Ramanathan, 2001; Shen et al., 2009). In general, railway has a potential advantage over road transport, in terms of long haul and mass scale traffic movements (passenger and freight). Besides, rail transport also contributes less significantly towards environmental degradation in comparison to road transport (Chapman, 2007; Givoni et al., 2009; Nelldal and Andersson, 2012). A country’s effective railway transport system facilitates com­ merce and trade, reduces transportation costs and road congestion, promotes national integration and rural development (Government of Pakistan, 2013).
Rail freight demand is an important component of rail operations. The demand for rail freight transport services are derived in nature just like the demand for many other inputs such as labor, energy etc. by the firms. Freight transport is usually considered as an input to the production process of firms and it is derived from the demand for goods spatially differentiated from the locations of production. The two important determinants of demand for rail freight transport are economic activity and price, among other factors

