M.Z. Khan and F.N. Khan

Journal of Rail Transport Planning & Management 14 (2020) 100176

2005; Oum et al., 1990, 1992; Winston, 1983; Zlatoper and Austrian, 1989). In their review of road and rail freight market elasticities, Oum et al. (1990) examine 17 freight studies from Asia-pacific, UK and North America and report estimates pertaining to all major commodity groups and grains only. According to their survey, price elasticities regarding all commodities are in a range of-0.60 to À 1.52, whereas those of grains are between À 0.52 and À 1.18. The analysts also provide the possible reasons for obtaining a wide range of elasticities in existing literature. These are intensity of inter-modal competition between different modes, differences in geographic locations and time horizons, degree of aggregation in markets and use of different functional forms (Oum et al., 1992).
Rail freight transport demand studies, based on time series data, are generally aggregate in nature and incorporate few broad macroeconomic variables for estimation. Recent studies employ multivariate time series econometric methods such as co-integration and vector autoregressive models to analyze aggregate freight transport demand (Kulshreshtha et al., 2001; Ramanathan, 2001; Wijeweera et al., 2014). Ramanathan (2001) examines long-run association between the performance of Indian transport sector using two-step Engle-Granger co-integration and error correction model. An aggregate passenger and freight transport activity of three modes road, rail and air is added together to develop a separate econometric model for both passenger and freight transport. Using annual data for period 1956–1989, study finds that long-run freight demand is determined by the industrial production and price index. The estimated long-run output and price elasticities of freight transport are 1.183 and À 0.188 while their values in the short-run are 0.994 and 0.072, respectively. The error correction term shows that ton-kilometers adjust 40% in the first year to restore its long-run equilibrium.
A major limitation of Ramanathan’s study is presumption of existence of at most one co-integrating vector even for multi variables case and also does not treat the possible endogeneity of explanatory variables well. Kulshreshtha et al. (2001) recognize these issues in their analysis of freight transport demand for Indian railways. They employ the Johansen co-integration and error correction model on annual time series data for period 1960–1995. The empirical results show that a unique long-run co-integration relationship exists among rail freight demand, freight-rate and GDP. The long-run output and price elasticities of rail freight demand are 0.86 and À 0.20 while the short-run elasticities are smaller than their long-run values. Furthermore, the system corrects itself within 3 years from any short-run disequilibrium through the adjustments in GDP and freight transport demand while price variable (real freight rate) behave weakly exogenous with respect to the system.
Wijeweera et al. (2014) apply the concept of Vector Autoregressive (VAR) model on an annual data for the period 1970–2011 to examine the effect of business cycle (GDP), freight rate and international trade (nominal exchange rate) on non-bulk Australian rail freight demand, treating all variables symmetrically (endogenous). The results derived from impulse response functions (IRF) and forecast error variance decompositions reveal that two most important determinants of rail freight demand are freight rate and variation in Australian dollar. In particular, a depreciation of Australian dollar promotes rail freight demand in Australia. Moreover, authors also find that, in the long-run, there exists negative and significant association between freight-rate and rail freight demand whereas the effect of GDP on Australian non-bulk rail freight demand is negative albeit insignificant.
Few studies employ several econometric methods for freight demand estimation and analyze the differences in estimation results (Chung and Kang, 2015; Shen et al., 2009). Shen et al. (2009) utilize six econometric models to derive empirical estimates of output elasticities for both aggregate road plus rail freight transport as well as for different commodity groups and compare elasticities using different econometric techniques. These econometric models are traditional ordinary least square (OLS) regression model, partial adjustment model (PAM), reduced auto-regressive distributed lag (ADL) model, unrestricted vector auto-regressive (VAR) model, time varying parameter (TVP) model and structural time series (STS) model. The authors find some variation in resulting coefficients (elasticities) derived from various techniques. The estimated long-run output elasticities range from 0.720 to 1.485. The study also compares the forecasting performance of all models using Mean Absolute Prediction error (MAPE) criteria and finds that no single model outperforms others in all situations.
Andersson and Elger (2012) investigate empirical relationship between Swedish freight transport (aggregate as well as for each specific mode such as road, rail, and sea) and economic activity (GDP, industrial production, imports and exports) at three different time horizons (short-run, medium-run and long-run) using annual time series data for the period 1996 to 2007. The study adopts Engle, (1974) band spectrum regression as a method of estimation. According to this model, each variable is first decomposed into different components (short, medium and long-run) and then a different model is estimated for each time horizon. The results indicate that all variation (volatility) in freight demand from short to medium-run is mainly driven by temporary changes in exports and imports while GDP remains insignificant. However, in long-run, GDP coupled with freight demand exert a significant positive impact on freight transport demand for all transport modes. The long-run income elasticities, for different transport modes, vary between 0.9 and 2.6.

2.1. Previous studies on rail freight transport in Pakistan

Although some empirical freight transport studies exist for Pakistan, none of them have investigated the issue of demand for rail freight transport properly. For instance, Beenish et al. (2016) explore the nexus between railways freight performance (measured as goods transported) and economic growth (GNI growth-rate) in Pakistan for period 1980–2012. The study employs Johansen co-integration and error correction test based on Fully Modified Ordinary Least Square (FIML) to estimate the existence of stable long-run relationship between above stated variables. The results indicate that a stable long-run relationship exists between rail freight performance and economic growth and also that only economic growth (GNI growth-rate) responds to short-run deviations to re-establish long-run equilibrium relationship whereas freight performance remains weakly exogenous to the system. Moreover, Granger causality test indicates that weak uni-directional causality runs from economic growth to rail freight performance.
In a different perspective, Choudhary et al. (2009) treat road & rail transport activity as transport infrastructure and analyze freight transport infrastructure in Pakistan using Porter’s (1980) framework for time series data from 1990 to 2008. The forecasting freight

6

M.Z. Khan and F.N. Khan

Journal of Rail Transport Planning & Management 14 (2020) 100176

transport demand (road, rail and aggregate) until 2030 based on historical trend analysis reveals that road freight demand will likely to grow continuously at an annual growth rate of 6.2%–7.2% provided that the GDP growth rate remains 6% or above. According to the freight projections, the share of road freight transport will remain a major and dominant mode with a share of 95% in terms of freight movement while share of rail freight transport will continue to remain at 5% or less in future.

3. Methodology and data related issues

The variable definitions and data related issues will be explained in the next section while details about econometric model for rail freight demand will be provided thereafter.

3.1. Variables and Data Sources

Our objective is to analyze the major determinants of rail freight demand using time series data. Different indicators can be used to represent rail freight demand such as (1) freight moved by its weight (measured in thousand or million tons) and (2) freight moved by both its weight and distance covered (measured by ton-kilometers). We measure rail freight demand by ton-kilometers, which is a more appropriate measure of freight demand. Many empirical rail freight studies have used ton-kilometer or ton-miles as a measure of rail freight transport demand (see, for example, Kulshreshtha et al., 2001; Rao, 1978; Wijeweera et al., 2014). We focus on the major factors affecting rail freight demand in Pakistan.
Freight Rate: Rail freight demand, like demand for many other products, is a function of its own price, which is rail freight rate. Rail freight rate is the rate charged by rail authorities for moving freight (measured as ton-kilometers) from its origins to destinations. Since time series data on actual rail freight rate is not available for Pakistan, we use a proxy of rail freight rate as average-rate-chargedper-ton-per-kilometer. It can be derived by taking ratio of total annual rail freight earnings to total annual ton-kilometers performed by rail freight. The expected sign of the coefficient associated with freight rate is negative (as per law of demand).
Gross Value Added (GVA): Since freight transport can also be perceived as an input or cost in production process, it can also be related to economic activity. There are number of indicators that can be used to represent aggregate economic activity. These are gross domestic product (GDP), gross value added (GVA) and industrial production. All three indicators have been used in aggregate empirical freight transport studies for economic activity (Andersson and Elger, 2012; Kulshreshtha et al., 2001; Shen et al., 2009). However, gross value added (GVA) quantifies the value added to goods and services produced and represent the contribution to the economy by producers or wider industry. The gross values added (GVA) by goods producing sector is more closely related to goods movements than GDP. So, therefore, we measure the economic activity by making use of gross value added (GVA), which can be a better measure of aggregate domestic production activities.
International Trade: Trade variable is included in our model to capture the impact of goods movements with other trading countries on rail freight demand in Pakistan. Theoretically, an increase in trade with other countries is likely to increase aggregate freight demand in Pakistan, including rail freight. Some of existing aggregate empirical rail freight studies have also incorporated trade variable in their analysis (see, for example, Andersson and Elger, 2012; Wijeweera et al., 2014) We measure international trade as sum of imports and exports of Pakistan and expressed in local currency units (million rupees).
Fuel Price: Trucking is the main competitor of rail freight in Pakistan. However, time series data regarding trucking rates are not available. Therefore, fuel price, particularly the price of high-speed diesel is used as an approximation for trucking costs. So, fuel price is used to measure the cross-price elasticity of rail freight transport. The previous studies have estimated the cross-price elasticity of rail freight transport (FitzRoy and Smith, 1995; Oum, 1989) The expected sign of fuel price is positive and is measured in rupees/liter.
In addition, many service quality indicators such as route coverage, frequency and reliability are also highly relevant to rail freight transport. However, the absence of long time series data on these variables limits their use in our analysis.
The time series data on ton-kilometers and average revenue per-ton-per-kilometer is taken from various issues of Pakistan Railway Yearbook (PRY). The data regarding fuel (diesel) price is obtained from various issues of Pakistan Energy Yearbook (PEY). The data related to international trade and gross value added (GVA) is taken from the Handbook of Statistics on Pakistan Economy (2015).

3.2. Econometric model

Our theoretical model of rail freight demand is given as follows:
TKMt ¼ fðF Rt; GVAt; Tradet; Fuel PricetÞ
Symbols TKM F_R GVA

(3.1)
Variables
Ton-kilometer Freight-rate Gross value added

Rail freight demand model in equation (3.1) is only a theoretical (mathematical) model. For estimation, an empirical log-log specification of equation (3.2) can be written as follows:

lnTKMt ¼ ∅0 þ ∅1lnðF RtÞ þ ∅2 lnðGVAtÞ þ ∅3 lnðTradetÞ þ ∅4 lnðFuel PricetÞ þ ut

(3.2)

7

M.Z. Khan and F.N. Khan

Journal of Rail Transport Planning & Management 14 (2020) 100176

Here ut is the error-term of estimated model. The ∅i’s parameters represent the long-run elasticities of rail freight demand. Since we are dealing with time series data, it is suitable to first consider the stationarity properties of all variables before selecting any appropriate econometric method. Many aggregate time series variables, in most cases, follow non-stationary behavior (stochastic trend). However, ignoring non-stationarity, in a regression model, may provide spurious relationships and invalid statistical inferences (Lin and Brannigan, 2003; Shrestha and Bhatta, 2018). The stationary or non-stationary behavior of a time series is generally verified on the basis of unit root tests. Two popular unit root tests are augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test and Phillip-Perron (PP) test, proposed by Dickey and Fuller (1979) and Phillips and Perron (1988). The null hypothesis of both ADF and PP tests are based on the assumption that the underlying series (variable) is non-stationary while the series is stationary in alternative hypothesis. A variable will be considered non-stationary if the test statistic of both ADF and PP tests happens to be greater than the relevant critical values associated with these tests. For appropriate statistical analysis, the non-stationary series can be transformed to a stationary process through differencing, which depends on the integrated order of a non-stationary series. However, when all variables in a regression model are non-stationary with same order of integration (integrated of order one e-g. I(1)), then time series econometric literature suggests for testing the co-integration relationship between them. The basic idea of co-integration is that if a linear combination of non-stationary variables is stationary, then variables are cointegrated. The two common tests of co-integration are two-step Engle-Granger test and system based Johansen co-integration test, proposed by Engle and Granger (1987) and Johansen (1988). We choose Johansen co-integration and vector error correction model to estimate both long and short-run elasticities of rail freight demand. The choice of Johansen’s system based method is more appropriate in case of multi variables. In general, at most ‘k-1’ co-integrating relationships may exist for ‘k’ number of variables in a system. However, testing ‘k-1’ co-integrating relationships for ‘k’ variables is not possible in Engle-Granger co-integration test. Moreover, Johansen co-integration test may also be superior over Engle-Granger test when feedback effects from price (freight rate) are important for decisions regarding the demand for rail freight transport (Kulshreshtha et al., 2001). Johansen’s co-integration procedure is based on following steps: First, an unrestricted reduced form vector autoregressive (VAR) model, containing all variables (such as ton-kilometers, freight rate, gross value added, international trade and fuel price), will be estimated for various lags and then a model with optimal lag length will be determined using some information criterion. Two most useable criterions, Schwarz information criterion (SIC) and Akaike information criterion (AIC), will be used. Second, Johansen proposed two likelihood ratio tests as trace statistic (λtrace) and maximum-eigenvalue statistic (λmax) to determine the existence and number of co-integrating relationships. For ‘k’ variables, the trace statistic proceeds sequentially by testing the null hypothesis of exactly ‘r’ co-integrating vectors (where r ¼ 0, 1, 2, …., k) against a more general alternative hypothesis of testing more than ‘r’ co-integrating vectors until we fail to reject the null. Maximum-eigenvalue test is similar to trace statistic except for the alternative hypothesis. The alternative hypothesis in maximum-eigenvalue statistic tests for exactly ‘r þ 1’co-integrating vectors instead of testing a general more than ‘r’ co-integrating vectors. If both likelihood ratio tests provide evidence in favor of existence of unique co-integration relationship, then long-run relationship among the determinants of rail freight demand is provided by equation (3.2) whereas ∅i’s are treated as long-run elasticities. Finally, error correction model is used to capture the short-run dynamics of model. The short-run error correction model of rail freight demand is given by the following equation:

