λ represents the error correction term such that À 1 < λ < 0, otherwise short-run deviations from long-run equilibrium relationship will not converge back to the equilibrium as time elapses. In that case, it makes short-run error correction model inconsistent with longrun. Moreover, the significance of error correction term further reinforces the long-run co-integration relationship. Parameters l1, l2, l3, l4 and m are the optimal lags to be selected so as to make residuals et white-noise whereas others b10, b20, b30, and b40 are treated as short-run elasticities of rail freight demand.

4. Results and discussion

The pre-requisite of Johansen co-integration analysis is to first check for time series properties of each individual series. To provide consistency to the results, we employ two unit root tests namely augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) and Phillips-Perron (PP) test on each individual series to determine the order of integration and results are provided in Table 3. As both tests performed on each variable, the null hypothesis of unit root at level cannot be rejected except for the trade, where the null of unit root is marginally rejected at 10% level of significance. However, null hypothesis of unit root is significantly rejected when applied to the first difference of each series. Consequently, it can be concluded that all the variables are integrated of order one e-g. I(1) processes.

