Notes: Both ADF and PP tests involve regression with intercept only. Each variable is converted in natural log form. The lag lengths are decided on the basis of Schwarz information Criterion (SIC) and optimal lag length for ADF test is given in parentheses. ***,** and * Indicates rejection of null hypothesis of unit root at 10%, 5% and 1% level of significance. The values in square-brackets represent the order of integration.

Since all variables are integrated of order one, it is meaningful to consider the long-run co-integration relationship between them with the help of Johansen co-integration test. First, an unrestricted vector autoregressive model (VAR) is estimated by considering all variables (ton-kilometers, freight rate, gross value added, trade and fuel price) as endogenous. Since rail freight has sharply declined for period 2010 to 2013, an exogenous dummy variable is also included in Johansen co-integration test to capture the outliers associated with the period 2010–2013. We generate dummy variable by using a value of ‘1’ in these four years from 2010 to 2013 and ‘0’ in all remaining years. The optimal lags are selected by estimating an unrestricted vector autoregressive model. Ignoring an optimal lag length may result in non-Gaussian residuals which can further invalidate the inferences. Table 4 provides the optimal lag length based on four different criterions. Majority of criterions suggest an optimal lag length of 2, except Schwarz information criterion (SIC). So, we select an optimum lag length of 2, given that our data is on annual basis. Moreover, at lag 2, the residuals from unrestricted vector autoregressive model are free from problems of serial correlation, heteroscedasticity and non-normality.
After selecting an optimal lag, we have performed the Johansen multivariate co-integration test to determine the existence and number of co-integration relationships. The results of Johansen co-integration analysis, based on two tests such as Trace statistic (represented by λtrace) and Maximum Eigen-value statistic (λmax value) along with 95% critical values are provided in Table 5. In comparison, testing for no co-integration or r ¼ 0 against at most one co-integrating vector, both values of λtrace and λmax are greater than their 5% critical values. However, further null hypothesis of one co-integrated vector against an alternative hypothesis of two or more co-integrated vectors cannot be rejected by the both tests. Hence both tests provide evidence in favor of the existence of unique long-run relationship.
We now move to the discussion regarding long-run elasticities of rail freight demand after having established a single long-run relationship represented by single co-integrating vector given in the last row of Table 5.
In order to interpret the long-run relationship, we need to reverse the sign of coefficients provided by the co-integrating vector.6 The first determinant of rail freight demand is freight rate (F_R), which has a significant negative relationship with rail freight demand, confirming the law of demand. The long-run elasticity of rail freight demand with respect to freight rate is À 0.39, which is quite inelastic. It means that all else equal if rail authorities increase the freight rate by 10%, as a result, the demand for rail freight transport will decrease by 3.9%, which is less than the increase in average freight rate in percentage term. This relationship is significant at 5% level. It implies that rail management can increase its freight revenues by increasing average freight rate without reducing much of its freight, due to the inelastic nature of price elasticity of rail freight demand.
Some earlier empirical studies on aggregate rail freight demand have also estimated a significant but low freight price effect. For example, Kulshreshtha et al. (2001) analyze rail freight demand for Indian railways and find that own price (freight rate) elasticities are significant, with coefficient of elasticities are in a range of À 0.099 to À 0.287, for all samples used in the study. Wijeweera et al. (2014) estimate Australian non-bulk rail freight demand with the help of vector auto-regressive (VAR) model and the results show that freight rate exerts a negative significant effect on rail freight demand.
The effect of economic activity (measured as gross values added (GVA) on rail freight demand is positive and the relationship is also significant at 1% level. The result, in terms of elasticity, can be interpreted as follows; a 10% increase in gross value added (GVA) will produce 0.84% increase in rail freight demand. The relationship between gross value added and rail freight demand is relatively more sensitive and elastic. Our results are, in general, similar to the existing empirical literature of aggregate rail freight studies that the relationship between rail freight demand and economic activity (different indicators) is positive and significant. For example, Kul­ shreshtha et al. (2001) observe a positive and significant effect of GDP on aggregate rail freight demand for India, with GDP elasticity varies between 0.83 and 0.91. Ramanathan (2001) also find that the long-run elasticity of aggregate (air, rail and road) freight

