transport with respect to industrial output is 1.18. Similarly, Shen et al. (2009) use six econometric models to estimate the relationship between UK aggregate (road plus rail) freight
transport demand and industrial production. The results indicate that long-run production elasticity of road plus rail freight, based on four econometric models, is greater than 1. We also find that international trade and rail freight are negatively related. However, the observed relationship is not significant at conventional levels.
On the other hand, the cross price elasticity of rail freight demand with respect to trucking cost (fuel price) is 0.25, which is statistically significant at 10% level. In particular, a 10% increase in trucking cost is associated with an increase in rail freight demand by 2.5%. The variation in rail freight demand with respect to trucking cost is quite inelastic. It implies that road and rail are substitutes in handling domestic inland freight transport. However, the effect of trucking cost (fuel price) on rail freight is less dominant because trucking provides relatively more reliable, certain, flexible and door-to-door services as compared to rail. FitzRoy and Smith (1995) also estimate the impact of trucking cost (diesel price) on the demand for rail freight transport of fifteen European countries. Their results show that rail freight elasticity of trucking cost is 0.93, which is statistically significant at 10% level of significance.

4.1. Discussion on the short-run elasticities of rail freight demand in Pakistan
After discussing the long-run elasticities of rail freight demand in Pakistan, we now consider the short-run error correction model of rail freight demand. To measure the long-run relationships, an optimal lag length of 2 is selected. Since all variables are used in differenced form to estimate the short-run parameters, the optimal lag 1 is used for error correction model. The results are reported in Table 6. All coefficients corresponding to the first difference of right side variables are treated as short-run elasticities.
The short-run elasticities are significantly lower than the long-run elasticities. Moreover, all short-run elasticities are also statis­ tically significant, except for trade and fuel price. In particular, the freight rate and production elasticities of rail freight, in short-run, are À 0.28 and 0.51, respectively. Both elasticities are highly significant at 1% level of significance. However, short-run cross price elasticity is positive but insignificant. It implies that an increase in cost of trucking, in short-run, will not induce the road shippers to substitute rail for their shipments. This may happen due to different factors, such as uncertainty associated with rail operations, limited capacity (freight wagons and locomotives) and less flexibility. The dummy variable is negative and highly significant at 1% level. Since it is used to capture the outliers in rail freight, its significance provides further justification of its use in the rail freight model.
An important feature of short-run rail freight demand equation is the error-correction term ECTt-1, which matters for the stability of long-run model of rail freight demand. The value of error correction term is À 0.53 and is significant at 1% level. It shows that, for any last period deviations (errors) from long-run relationship, short-run adjustment in rail freight demand takes place in such a way that 53% of the deviation from long-run equilibrium is corrected in the following period to restore the long-run equilibrium relationship.
We now discuss the overall performance of short-run rail freight demand model. Panel 1 in Table 6 contains the model’s di­ agnostics. F-statistic also provides further evidence that all explanatory variables in the model are significant. Finally, Durbin-Watson statistic suggests that residuals of short-run rail freight demand are free from autocorrelation.
In addition, a number of diagnostic tests are performed which assist us to check the appropriateness of estimated short-run model of rail freight demand. The results are given by panel 2 in Table 6. A high p-value of Breusch-Godfrey LM test implies that null of no residual serial correlation cannot be rejected. So, the residuals are free of serial correlation. For testing heteroscedasticity in residuals, we performed Harvey test and observed that p-value is greater than 5% significance level, showing no sign of heteroscedasticity in model’s residuals at 5% level of significance.7 Similarly, we also find that there is no autoregressive conditional heteroskedastic (ARCH) effect in the residuals. Finally, reported value of Jarque-Bera test is low, which implies that residuals are normally distributed.
5. Conclusion
Rail is preferable mode of transport in terms of handling long haul freight and also because of less deteriorating impact on envi­ ronmental quality. In this study, we analyzed the empirical relationship between aggregate rail freight transport demand in Pakistan and its determinants such as economic activity, freight rate, international trade and fuel price. For that, time series data is used for period 1972–2017. The unit root tests like augmented Dickey-Fuller and Phillips-Perron tests have shown that all variables are in­ tegrated of order one. The Johansen co-integration and error correction model is employed to estimate the short and long-run elas­ ticities of rail freight demand.
The estimation results show that freight rate and aggregate economic activity (gross value added) are most significant determinants of rail freight demand in Pakistan, both in the short and long-run. We have also estimated the cross price elasticity of rail freight demand with respect to trucking cost and have found that long-run cross price elasticity is positive and significant at 10% level. Moreover, ECM is estimated to capture the short-run elasticities and dynamics. The speed of adjustment coefficient has indicated that 53% of the error, committed in the previous period, is corrected in the following period to restore the long-run equilibrium. Finally, several diagnostic tests have been conducted to ascertain the validity of estimated elasticities from the ECM. These tests proposed that estimated model is valid and can further be used for forecasting and policy purposes.
The estimated long-run aggregate economic activity and freight rate elasticities of rail freight transport are 0.84 and À 0.39 while the same elasticities, in the short-run, are 0.51 and À 0.28, respectively. Since short and long-run freight rate elasticities are both quite

7 we omit White heteroskedasticity test due to the number of insufficient observations to perform the test. 11

M.Z. Khan and F.N. Khan

Journal of Rail Transport Planning & Management 14 (2020) 100176

inelastic, it implies that rail authorities can increase freight revenues by raising freight rate, without losing most of the freight. The additional freight revenues may either be used to reduce the huge deficit of Pakistan railway or to purchase more freight wagons and locomotives. On the other hand, economic activity elasticities of rail freight demand are relatively more elastic and offer important implications for rail freight. It indicates that the demand for rail freight will likely to increase with the economic growth of Pakistan. Similarly, the long-run cross price elasticity, with a value of 0.25, also suggest that rail freight is likely to increase with the cost of trucking, measured by fuel price. So, increasing the road fuel taxes, particularly on the high-speed diesel, can be helpful for modal split in favor of rail freight.
The Government of Pakistan, in its official document of vision 2025, aims to increase the share of rail from 4% to 20% during 10 years from 2015 to 2025 (Planning Commission, 2014). For that, it adopts different strategies and investment plans to achieve its objective. The above analysis may also be helpful for planners in this regard. So, our analysis suggests that rail freight is likely to increase in the future as a result of economic growth in the country. Moreover, increase in trucking costs and prudent policies regarding freight rates are also important for promoting rail freight transport in Pakistan.

